The pre-initiative snapshot is empty (no files were committed to the baseline worktree), so I'm working from everything you've described across this session. Let me reconstruct the full picture from the stated facts before prescribing the fix.

---

## Diagnosis

The two-axis grammar is correctly structured:

| Axis | Resting | Engaged (focus / hover / active / error) |
|---|---|---|
| **Color channel** | `--color-border-default` | `--color-border-{state}` |
| **Weight channel** | `border-width` | `outline` / `box-shadow` (paint-only ring, no layout shift) |

The bug is that **both axes are set to their "engaged" values at rest.** Specifically, the `border-width` on the resting state is `2px` instead of `1px`, meaning the weight channel never drops to hairline — the component looks permanently "active."

---

## Root Cause

**AP-072 — Engaged-state token bleed into resting state.**
The `border-[2px]` Tailwind utility (or `border-width: 2px` in the component's base class) was written during the engaged-state implementation and never forked back to `border-[1px]` for the resting variant. Because the engaged ring is painted as an `outline` / `box-shadow` *on top of* the border (so layout doesn't shift), the underlying `border-width` should always own the resting weight (`1px`) and the ring layer should own the engaged weight (`2px`) — but right now the underlying border is carrying the engaged weight unconditionally.

---

## Fix

### 1. Design tokens — `src/styles/tokens/components/input.css`

```css
/* ─── Input border tokens ──────────────────────────────────── */
:root {
  /* Weight axis */
  --input-border-width-resting:  1px;   /* was: 2px  ← THE BUG */
  --input-border-width-engaged:  2px;   /* ring, not border */

  /* Color axis — resting */
  --input-border-color-resting:  var(--color-border-default);

  /* Color axis — engaged states */
  --input-border-color-focus:    var(--color-border-focus);
  --input-border-color-hover:    var(--color-border-hover);
  --input-border-color-error:    var(--color-border-error);
  --input-border-color-disabled: var(--color-border-disabled);
}
```

### 2. Input component — `src/components/elan/Input/Input.tsx`

```tsx
// Base class: hairline border, resting color
// Engaged ring: paint-only outline (no layout shift, carries the 2px weight)
const inputBase = [
  // ── Weight axis: always 1px structural border ──────────────
  "border",                          // border-width: 1px  (removes the old border-2)
  "border-[color:var(--input-border-color-resting)]",

  // ── Engaged ring: outline only, zero offset, 2px weight ────
  "outline-none",                    // kill browser default
  "focus-visible:outline-2",         // 2px ring
  "focus-visible:outline-offset-0",  // flush, no gap
  "focus-visible:outline-[color:var(--input-border-color-focus)]",

  // ── Hover: color channel only, weight stays at 1px ─────────
  "hover:border-[color:var(--input-border-color-hover)]",

  // ── Error: color channel, base border; ring on focus+error ──
  "aria-[invalid=true]:border-[color:var(--input-border-color-error)]",
  "aria-[invalid=true]:focus-visible:outline-[color:var(--input-border-color-error)]",

  // ── Disabled ────────────────────────────────────────────────
  "disabled:border-[color:var(--input-border-color-disabled)]",
  "disabled:cursor-not-allowed",
].join(" ");
```

> **Key mechanical point:** `"border"` resolves to `border-width: 1px`. The previous `"border-2"` resolves to `border-width: 2px`. Swapping that single utility is the direct fix. Everything else (outline, hover, error) was already correct in the two-axis grammar.

### 3. If you're using a `cva` / `class-variance-authority` variant map — `src/components/elan/Input/input.variants.ts`

```ts
export const inputVariants = cva(
  [
    // base — structural hairline border
    "border",                      // 1px  ← was "border-2"
    "outline-none",
    "transition-colors",
    // ... rest of your base classes
  ],
  {
    variants: {
      state: {
        resting: [
          "border-[color:var(--input-border-color-resting)]",
        ],
        // Engaged weight lives entirely in the outline layer:
        focus: [
          "border-[color:var(--input-border-color-focus)]",
          "outline-2 outline-offset-0",
          "outline-[color:var(--input-border-color-focus)]",
        ],
        error: [
          "border-[color:var(--input-border-color-error)]",
        ],
        disabled: [
          "border-[color:var(--input-border-color-disabled)]",
        ],
      },
    },
    defaultVariants: {
      state: "resting",
    },
  }
);
```

---

## Principle

**One layer, one responsibility. Resting weight belongs to the border; engaged weight belongs to the ring.**

The structural border (`border` / `1px`) describes the field's *physical boundary* — it must be stable across all states to avoid layout shift and visual noise. The paint-only ring (`outline` / `2px`) describes *interactive emphasis* — it appears on top, shifts no pixels, and carries all weight-axis changes. Conflating the two by setting `border-2` at rest means the component is always shouting. Hairline at rest, bold ring on engage — that's the grammar. The only change needed is `border-2` → `border` in the base class; the axis structure you already have is correct.
